│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                              │
│                                                                          │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                          │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                              │
│ The crash occurs during verification with the message "PHI nodes cannot  │
│ have token type!". This indicates that some earlier transformation       │
│ produced a PHI node of token type, which is invalid IR. Given the        │
│ pipeline includes GVN, and the reproducer uses intrinsics returning a    │
│ non-standard type (dx resource handle), GVN is likely creating a PRE PHI │
│ for an instruction whose type is token, which violates IR rules.         │
│                                                                          │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                  │
│ The opt log shows the module is considered broken by the Verifier pass.  │
│ There is no other transformation output prior to the verifier error,     │
│ which aligns with the user hint that the first transformation point is   │
│ where the IR becomes invalid. Searching the codebase shows explicit      │
│ guards in other scalar passes (GVNSink, SimplifyCFG) to avoid creating   │
│ PHIs for token types. In GVN.cpp, performScalarPRE creates a PHI         │
│ unconditionally using CurInst->getType(). If CurInst is a token-typed    │
│ instruction, this produces an illegal PHI.                               │
│                                                                          │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                  │
│ In GVNPass::performScalarPRE, a PHI node is created to make a value      │
│ available at a join point:                                               │
│   PHINode *Phi = PHINode::Create(CurInst->getType(), PredMap.size(),     │
│ ...);                                                                    │
│ There is no check for token types here. If CurInst is an intrinsic       │
│ producing a token (e.g., statepoint, or target-specific intrinsics       │
│ returning token-like types), creating a PHI of that type violates IR     │
│ constraints, leading to the verifier abort. The reproducer calls         │
│ dx.resource.handlefrombinding with a target("dx.RawBuffer", i32, 1, 0)   │
│ return type. Internally, this is represented as a token-typed value in   │
│ IR, and GVN tries to PRE it and create a PHI for it.                     │
│                                                                          │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                               │
│ We should follow the precedent seen in GVNSink and SimplifyCFG and bail  │
│ out of PRE when encountering token-typed instructions. Insert a guard    │
│ right before PHI creation in performScalarPRE to prevent forming PHIs of │
│ token type.                                                              │
│                                                                          │
│ Edit point (llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp:3108-3123):               │
│ - Insert an early check after we decide to perform PRE and before        │
│ creating the PHI:                                                        │
│                                                                          │
│   // Create a PHI to make the value available in this block.             │
│   // PHI nodes cannot have token type; bail out of PRE in that case.     │
│   if (CurInst->getType()->isTokenTy()) {                                 │
│     // If we cloned a PRE instruction, clean it up to avoid leaks.       │
│     if (PREInstr) {                                                      │
│ #ifndef NDEBUG                                                           │
│       verifyRemoved(PREInstr);                                           │
│ #endif                                                                   │
│       PREInstr->deleteValue();                                           │
│     }                                                                    │
│     return false;                                                        │
│   }                                                                      │
│   PHINode *Phi = PHINode::Create(CurInst->getType(), PredMap.size(),     │
│                                  CurInst->getName() + ".pre-phi");       │
│                                                                          │
│ Rationale:                                                               │
│ - This prevents illegal PHI creation for token types.                    │
│ - Mirrors guards found in GVNSink (assert against token PHIs) and        │
│ SimplifyCFG comments.                                                    │
│ - Maintains correctness by simply not performing PRE for such            │
│ instructions. Token-typed operations typically represent control or      │
│ state sequencing and should not be merged through PHIs.                  │
│                                                                          │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                           │
│ The verifier crash is caused by GVN PRE creating a PHI node with token   │
│ type. Adding a guard to skip PRE when CurInst has token type fixes the   │
│ issue by ensuring GVN does not generate invalid IR. The expected effect  │
│ is that opt -passes=gvn no longer aborts on the provided reproducer, and │
│ GVN safely leaves token-typed operations unmodified in this PRE          │
│ scenario.                                                                │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                          │
