  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs during
verification with the message \"PHI nodes cannot have token type!\". This
indicates that some earlier transformation produced a PHI node of token
type, which is invalid IR. Given the pipeline includes GVN, and the
reproducer uses intrinsics returning a non-standard type (dx resource
handle), GVN is likely creating a PRE PHI for an instruction whose type is
token, which violates IR rules.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt log
shows the module is considered broken by the Verifier pass. There is no
other transformation output prior to the verifier error, which aligns with
the user hint that the first transformation point is where the IR becomes
invalid. Searching the codebase shows explicit guards in other scalar passes
(GVNSink, SimplifyCFG) to avoid creating PHIs for token types. In GVN.cpp,
performScalarPRE creates a PHI unconditionally using CurInst->getType(). If
CurInst is a token-typed instruction, this produces an illegal PHI.\n\n3.
Root Cause Analysis:\nIn GVNPass::performScalarPRE, a PHI node is created to
make a value available at a join point:\n  PHINode *Phi =
PHINode::Create(CurInst->getType(), PredMap.size(), ...);\nThere is no check
for token types here. If CurInst is an intrinsic producing a token (e.g.,
statepoint, or target-specific intrinsics returning token-like types),
creating a PHI of that type violates IR constraints, leading to the verifier
abort. The reproducer calls dx.resource.handlefrombinding with a
target(\"dx.RawBuffer\", i32, 1, 0) return type. Internally, this is
represented as a token-typed value in IR, and GVN tries to PRE it and create
a PHI for it.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should follow the precedent
seen in GVNSink and SimplifyCFG and bail out of PRE when encountering
token-typed instructions. Insert a guard right before PHI creation in
performScalarPRE to prevent forming PHIs of token type.\n\nEdit point
(llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp:3108-3123):\n- Insert an early check
after we decide to perform PRE and before creating the PHI:\n\n  // Create a
PHI to make the value available in this block.\n  // PHI nodes cannot have
token type; bail out of PRE in that case.\n  if
(CurInst->getType()->isTokenTy()) {\n    // If we cloned a PRE instruction,
clean it up to avoid leaks.\n    if (PREInstr) {\n#ifndef NDEBUG\n
verifyRemoved(PREInstr);\n#endif\n      PREInstr->deleteValue();\n    }\n
return false;\n  }\n  PHINode *Phi = PHINode::Create(CurInst->getType(),
PredMap.size(),\n                                 CurInst->getName() +
\".pre-phi\");\n\nRationale:\n- This prevents illegal PHI creation for token
types.\n- Mirrors guards found in GVNSink (assert against token PHIs) and
SimplifyCFG comments.\n- Maintains correctness by simply not performing PRE
for such instructions. Token-typed operations typically represent control or
state sequencing and should not be merged through PHIs.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe verifier crash is caused by GVN PRE creating a PHI node
with token type. Adding a guard to skip PRE when CurInst has token type
fixes the issue by ensuring GVN does not generate invalid IR. The expected
effect is that opt -passes=gvn no longer aborts on the provided reproducer,
and GVN safely leaves token-typed operations unmodified in this PRE
scenario.",
